Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":47,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Littlebury Horne Lord Mayor of London was born in 1408, in Buckland, Hertfordshire, England, his father, Sir Henry James of Appledore Horne, was 19 and his mother, Lady Jane Howe, was 31. He died in 1469, in Shropshire, England, at the age of 61."},"et":{"1408–1469":"1408–1469","1430–1461":"1430–1461","1421–1465":"1421–1465","1409–1435":"1409–1435","1434–1499":"1434–1499","1438–1498":"1438–1498","1390–1441":"1390–1441","1378–Female":"1378–Surnud","1461":"1461","1390":"1390","1469":"1469","1435":"1435","1434":"1434","1455":"1455","1378":"1378","1499":"1499","about 1438":"umbes 1438","1498":"1498","1465":"1465","1421":"1421","1441":"1441","1430":"1430","about 1465":"umbes 1465","1409":"1409","1408":"1408","1438":"1438","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England